title: Appointment to Women's Commission
content_text:
p>
The Government today (January 5) announced the appointment of two new members 
and the re-appointment of two incumbent members to the Women's Commission. All 
appointments are for three years with effect from January 15, 2007. Two incumbent members, Ms Chau Chuen-heung and Ms Ko Po-ling, have been 
re-appointed. Ms Chau and Ms Ko have served on the Commission since January 
2004, and contributed to the promotion of further advancement of women in Hong

2004, and contributed to the promotion of further advancement of women in Hong 
Kong. The two new members are Ms Ayesha Abbas MacPherson and Mr Christopher Law Kin-chung. Ms MacPherson is a Partner of KPMG and the Deputy Chairman of the Community 
Services Committee of the Hong Kong Institute of Certified Public Accountants. 
She is committed to serving the community particularly for the promotion of the 
status of women and has actively participated in previous Women's Commission 
activities. Mr Law is an architect by profession, and he is the Director of Oval Partnership

activities. Mr Law is an architect by profession, and he is the Director of Oval Partnership 
Ltd. He is a member of the Commission on Strategic Development and the Social 
Worker Registration Board. Mr Law is actively serving the community through 
participation in the welfare sector. The Secretary for Health, Welfare and Food, Dr York Chow, welcomed the 
appointment of the two new members and the re-appointment of the two incumbent 
members. He looked forward to their contribution to the work for promoting the

members. He looked forward to their contribution to the work for promoting the 
well-being and interests of women in Hong Kong. Dr Chow also thanked the two outgoing members, Ms Ophelia Cheung and Mr Ng 
Sui-kou, for their valuable contribution and dedication to the work of the 
commission during their term of appointment. The Women's Commission was set up on January 15, 2001, as a high-level central 
mechanism that takes a strategic overview of women's issue. It plays a strategic 
role in advising the government on policies and initiatives that are of concern

role in advising the government on policies and initiatives that are of concern to women. Following is the membership list of the Women's Commission as from January 15, 2007: Non-official Members
